2 INTRODUCED BY K. BOGNER
3
4 A BILL FOR AN ACT ENTITLED: “AN ACT ESTABLISHING KILL SWITCH LAWS; PROHIBITING AN ENTITY
5 FROM REMOTELY ACTIVATING A KILL SWITCH WITHOUT A WARRANT; PROVIDING AN EXCEPTION;
6 PROVIDING DAMAGES; AND PROVIDING AN EFFECTIVE DATE.”
7
8 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
9
10 NEW SECTION. Section 1. Kill switches in electronic consumer products on personally owned
11 property -- warrant required -- exceptions -- definitions. (1) An entity may not activate a kill switch on an
12 individual's electronic consumer product personally owned property without a court order or a warrant issued
13 pursuant to Title 46, chapter 5, part 2.
14 (2) This section does not apply to subscriptions, memberships, and other recurring-payment
15 programs or to leased electronic consumer products. In the event an individual neglects to make regular
16 payments, the entity may activate a kill switch to turn off the individual's subscribed services.
17 (3) As used in [sections 1 and 2], the following definitions apply:
18 (a) "Electronic consumer product" includes electronic devices as defined in 45-6-310 as well as
19 motor vehicles as defined in 61-1-101.
20 (b)(a) "Entity" means a company that manufactures or distributes an electronic consumer product
21 personally owned property or that provides service for an electronic consumer product's its functionality.
22 (c)(b) “Hard reset” means the restoration of an electronic consumer product personally owned
23 property to the state the electronic consumer product it was in when it left the factory. Other terms commonly
24 used are "factory reset" and "master reset".
25 (d)(c) "Individual" means a natural person.
26 (e)(d) "Kill switch" means a mechanism that may be engaged remotely, regardless of the owner's
27 consent, and is used to:
